{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0f605f40-be47-4de9-90fb-932cde9ee1e5","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** (most likely):\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips`. Recent crashes appear here within seconds.\n\n2. **Console.app** — open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a formatted view of the same reports.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   # macOS disables core dumps by default. To enable:\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n   # Then reproduce the crash — the core file lands at /tmp/core.<pid>\n   ```\n\n4. **`/cores/`** — the default core dump directory (requires SIP adjustment on modern macOS, so Diagnostic Reports is usually easier).\n\n**Tip:** The `.ips` crash report includes the crash thread, stack trace, and signal info — often sufficient for diagnosing NativeAOT crashes without a full core dump.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6eeb1a30-9940-438b-bf00-c744362ffd7c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":324,"requestId":"D7C8:11B452:1038226:1289126:69F2B45F"},"id":"8ff810e4-4703-4229-b463-a482af44e17f","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:48:37.519Z","parentId":"396d5e02-0249-455e-a897-ad7c7e5e42a3"}
